Israel
[1] Epidemic
Date: Sun 14 Oct 2018 20:38 IDT
Source: Haaretz daily [in Hebrew, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
https://www.haaretz.co.il/news/health/.premium-1.6554499


Health officials are concerned about the spread of measles, warning that the Ministry of Health cannot stop it. The center of the epidemic is in the Jerusalem area, where 341 cases of measles have been detected since the beginning of the year [2018] -- more than half of the cases diagnosed countrywide. Last month [September 2018] the number of newly diagnosed measles cases reached 213. The number of new cases of measles in Israel in 2018 is 20-fold higher than in 2017.

A senior epidemiologist says, "15 new cases of measles are recorded every day in hospitals in Jerusalem. The medical teams do Sisyphean work and try to locate anyone who comes into contact with the patient; this is not fully achievable." According to the senior physician, if the Ministry of Health does not launch a nationwide publicity campaign that calls on the public to be vaccinated, it will spread to other areas.

In August 2018, the Health Ministry expressed concern about the outbreak of measles in the Jerusalem district [see references below], and the district physician, Dr Chen Stein Zamir, pointed out the low rates of vaccination and the increase in the number of people infected with the disease. In the past few weeks, there has been a further increase in the number of cases in Jerusalem.

"The outbreak is severe and we see it both in community clinics and in hospitals," said Yechiel Schlesinger, director of the Wilf Children's Hospital at Shaare Zedek Medical Center, who specializes in infectious diseases. "The problem in Jerusalem is in areas and populations, such as some ultra-Orthodox [Jewish] neighborhoods, where there are pockets of non-immunization, and not everyone is careful to be vaccinated." He said the children who arrive at the hospital are either infants under the age of one year who have not yet received the 1st dose and are therefore not protected from the disease, or older children who have not been vaccinated at all or have not received the 2nd dose. "At this stage we do not have patients in intensive care but there are children with severe pneumonia, and a pregnant woman who got infected and we have to treat her newborn with antibodies immediately after birth," says Schlesinger.

According to him, a large share of the resources of the medical teams is invested in isolating the patients and in locating everyone who had been in contact with them. "We try to make sure that every suspect case gets to the hospital, avoiding entering the central, main spaces of the building. We have even created a bypass route directly to the isolation ward, but this is a goal that cannot be 100 percent achieved". The dynamics of such epidemics are that they start from "pockets" from where they spread/leak. He believes that the low vaccination rate in some neighborhoods in Jerusalem does not necessarily stem from choice, but from lack of awareness.

The attempt to isolate patients in order to prevent infecting others has also been difficult. "We are trying to track the exposure and to check who has measles," says Prof Alon Mozes, director of the Department of Clinical Microbiology and Infectious Diseases at Hadassah Ein Karem Hospital. "But in Jerusalem we are close to losing control because there is a large population that is not vaccinated. We need to issue a call from the Ministry of Health and the heads of the ultra-Orthodox community urging to vaccinate."

According to Mozes, the diagnosed cases account for only one tenth of those who have not yet been diagnosed. "It is one of the most contagious diseases, many times more than the flu, which has a spread range of several meters. Measles infective particles are light and airborne and remain in the room's air space even 2 hours after the disease-carrier left the room. I am convinced that the number of cases is 10 times higher than the number of cases diagnosed, and is steadily growing", he says.

According to Dr Eli Schwartz, director of the Sheba-Tel Hashomer Center for Travel Medicine and Tropical Diseases, there are also vaccinants in Israel who are not protected against the disease. "There is a large segment of the population, born during the period of 1957-1977, who were immunized at a time when it was believed that one vaccination is sufficient, so their immunity is now partial." Schwartz adds that "the Ministry of Health primarily warns travelers to Europe and endemic countries, and it should simultaneously focus on populations that are not immune and call on them to be vaccinated."

[Byline: Iddo Efraty]

--
