[2] Vaccination
Date: Sun 14 Oct 2018 20:55 IDT
Source: Maariv daily [in Hebrew, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
https://www.maariv.co.il/news/israel/Article-665606


The Health Ministry is considering lowering the age of initial measles vaccination in toddlers from 1 year to 9 months of age. The report noted that since the beginning of the year [2018], 666 cases of measles [in all of Israel] have been reported to the Ministry of Health. This is a meteoric leap, and the fear is that the number will rise. The subject will be is on the agenda of a meeting this week. It should be noted that the vaccine is usually given at the age of 1 year.

Only 4 days ago, the Health Ministry in Jerusalem reported that a measles patient was on Israir flight 6H474, which left Eilat for the S'de Dov airport (Tel-Aviv] on 9 Oct 2018 at 13:55. The flight attendants said that if anyone on that flight were to develop fever and/or rash, they should inform their family doctor about having had contact with a measles patient.

In addition, passengers belonging to risk groups, including infants under the age of 12 months, pregnant women, people with immunodeficiency disorders (such as cancer patients during chemotherapy, patients treated with high-dose corticosteroids, or AIDS patients) are kindly requested to call by telephone as soon as possible to discuss the possible need for their vaccination.

A similar case was reported last month [September 2018] when the Ministry of Health announced that a passenger suspected of having measles had traveled on a number of flights from Israel to Kiev. Travelers with severe illnesses, pregnant women, and infants were then asked to be examined.

